comment.text: "Lyricist Harry Bache Smith was born in Buffalo, New York on December 28, 1860. In his early career, Smith was a music critic for the Chicago Daily News and later a drama critic for the Chicago Tribune. Smith moved to New York City and began collaborating on Broadway scores with composers Reginald De Koven, Victor Herbert, Jerome Kern, Sigmund Romberg and Ted Snyder. His stage scores include those for Whirl-i-Gig, The Enchantress, Love O’ Mike, Three Little Girls, The Begum, Don Quixote, Robin Hood, Jupiter, The Algerian, Rob Roy, The Wizard of the Nile, The Serenade, The Highwayman, The Fortune Teller, The Rounders, Papa’s Wife, The Casino Girl, The Strollers, Liberty Belies, The Little Duchess, The Billionaire, The Rich Mr. Hoggenheimer, The Persian Model, Ziegfeld Follies (1907, 1908, 1909, 1910 and 1912), Little Nemo, Miss Innocence, The Siren, The Doll Girl, The Rambler Rose, Ladies First, The Love Song, Princess Flavia, Naughty Riquette, Countess Maritza, The Circus Princess, White Lilacs, The Wild Rose, Spring Maid, The Red Rose, The Rose Maid, The Girl from Utah, Sybil, Angel Face, Caroline, The Love Call, The Red Robe, Nearly a Hero, Watch Your Step, Stop! Look! Listen!, Sweetheart Time, Gaby, Sweethearts and A Lonely Romeo. Smith is also the author of several novels including his autobiography, First Nights and First Editions, as well as introductions to Shakespeare and Dickens. He was also a charter member of the Association of Composers, Authors and Publishers (ASCAP) and served as a director from 1914-1917. Song highlights from the Smith stage productions include “The Sheik of Aray”, “Bright Eyes”, “Yours Is My Heart Alone”, “The Land of Let’s Pretend”, “Romany Life”, “Gypsy Love Song”, “To the Land of My Own Romance”, “Play Gypsies, Dance Gypsies”, “Dancing Fool”, “I Wonder Why”, “I Can’t Forget Your Eyes”, “Drift With Me”, “Don’t Tempt Me” and “I Wonder if You Still Care for Me”. Harry B. Smith died in Atlantic City, New Jersey on January 3, 1936." The above is from The Songwriters Hall of Fame web site. Harry Bache Smith's papers are among the collections at the Harry Ransom Research Center. From the Ransom Center's biographical sketch of him: "Smith wrote articles on literature and music for Scribner's, The Century, Harper's, Atlantic Monthly, American Mercury, and other magazines. He was also known by collectors of rare books, manuscripts, and autographs. Published in 1914, A Sentimental Library (available in the HRC book collection) is a catalogue of books, manuscripts, drawings, and presentation copies collected and described by Smith."

comment.text: Edith Anne Greene (d. 1912?; see below) was a notable designer of late 19th-century bookplates, particularly for women; cf. N. Labouchere, Ladies' Book-Plates (London: G. Bell & Sons, 1895), p. 168-171, and H.W. Fincham, Artists and Engravers of British and American Bookplates (London: Kegan Paul, Trench, Trübner & Co., 1897), p. 37. By 1895 she was a member of the Ex Libris Society and resident at 14 Royal Park, Clifton, Bristol, England; cf. W. Hamilton, Dated Book-Plates (London: A&C Black, 1895), p. 113. (K.E. Graf zu Leiningen-Westerburg also locates her in "Clifton Bristol" in his 1901 Deutsche und Oesterreichische Bibliothekzeichen Exlibris; cf. p. 558.) According to a solicitor's notice in The London Gazette 2 July 1912, a woman of that name resident at 15 Hanbury-road, Clifton, Bristol, died on 25 May 1912. This appears to be one of at least two bookplates she designed for herself; cf. J.F. Verster and W.H.K. Wright, "List of Landscape Bookplates" in Journal of the Ex Libris Society 10 (1900), p. 147.

Scripsi Noë Eytner. [Hand of Noë Eytner, recording the baptism of his son Joannes Eytner of Glatz (now Kłodzko) on 12 May 1602, along with the names of godparents and witnesses:
-- Johann von Sitsch (1552-1608), Prince-Bishop of Breslau (1600-1608) -- Abbot Mathias Camnicensis, i.e. of Kamnitz, probably a foundation in one of two towns now named Kamieniec in the neighborhood of Glatz -- Heinrich von Logau (d. 1625), Landeshauptmann of Glatz, Knight of the Order of Malta and Commander of the Commandery of Troppau. (His brother, Kaspar von Logau (1524-1574), was Prince-Bishop of Breslau from 1562-1574.) -- Heinrich von Ratschin (d. 1612), a minor noble whose principal seat appears to have been Arnsdorf (later Grafenort; now Gorzanów) -- Conradus, Maria, and Anna Adelsbach -- Friedrich von Walditz and his unnamed wife -- Gräfin von Pompsdorf, i.e. Anna Maria Popel von Lobkowitz (d. 1603), wife of Václav Graf Rozdrazovsky z Rozdrazova (or Wenzel Graf von Rozdrazow) (d. 1625), among whose minor titles was the lordship of Pompsdorf. She was the daughter of Georg Popel von Lobkowitz (1551-1607) who was imprisoned in Glatz at this time for intriguing against Emperor Rudolf II. See his entry in the Allgemeine Deutsche Biographie. -- Eva Eusebia von Lobkowitz (d. 1624), sister of Anna Maria, a well-educated woman and her father's partisan; her advocacy on his behalf led to her removal in 1605 from Glatz to St. George's Convent in Prague until his death. comment.text: Vellum leaf from a liturgical music ms. (possibly an antiphonary?), with 5-line staves in red and neumes and text in brown ink in a post-Gothic hand (not earlier than the 16th century, when the 5-line staff developed).  The text appears to be an antiphon based on Song of Songs 7:10 and 3:4:  "Ego dilecto meo et ad me conversio ejus; inveni quem diligit anima mea; tenui eum, nec dimittam."  Following her canonization in 1728, this antiphon was sung with the Magnificat (the canticle for vespers) on the feast of St. Margaret of Cortona (23 February).  I have been unable to determine if it was used any earlier or in any other context.

comment.text: Woodcut illustration (used by Erhard Oeglin of Augsburg) of a banner bearer for the Bundschuh Insurrections (1493-1517), a series of German peasant revolts linked by their use of the imagery of a tied shoe (Bundschuh, which can be seen on the ground at left). The bearer is possibly to be identified with Joss Fritz (ca. 1470-ca. 1525), who headed the 1513 insurrection in Lehen (now part of Freiburg im Breisgau) to which this work responds. The banner itself depicts Christ's crucifixion between the arms of Pope Julius II (right) and those of the Habsburg Holy Roman Emperors (left; effaced); this speaks to the first principle of Fritz's rebellion: "Erstens solle niemand mehr einen anderen Herrn als Gott, den Kaiser und den Papst anerkennen" [First, no one shall henceforth acknowledge any lord but God, the emperor, and the pope]. Established heading: Oeglin, Erhard, ‡d d. ca. 1520. Established heading: Fritz, Joss, ǂd ca. 1470-ca. 1525. Established heading: Bundschuh Insurrections, 1493-1517.

comment.author: 58584977@N05
comment.text:
I doubt it. I think Adriana is right and this is the men's house, Kloster St. Magadalena. Dominicans are first documented in Augsburg in 1225. The men's foundation (ca. 1225-1808) was Kloster St. Magdalena (also known as "Predigerkloster"). It was secularized in 1802, but some monks hung on in the church for another six years, according to this website. The community under this name is defunct; the current male Dominican presence in Augsburg (since 1931) is at Heilige Kreuz. (For comparison, here's an engraved bookplate of Kloster St. Magdalena from Kloster-Exlibris der Bayerischen Staatsbibliothek, Bd.: 1, A - D, ca. 1540-1800. Note that they're simply calling themselves "Conventus Augustani FF. Ord. Praed." Notre Dame also has a book with a late 16th-century inscription from the same house: "Sum Conventus Augustani FF. Praedicatorum.") On the women's side, Augsburg had three Dominican foundations (again according to this very useful website on Bavarian monasteries):
A group of Augsburger Beguines living in the neighborhood of Kloster St. Magdalena were placed under the Dominican rule in 1394 and were formally established as Dominicans, Third Order Regular, in 1431. Their name is Kloster St. Ursula. Although their foundation was secularized in 1802, the nuns were permitted to remain in the cloister and lived to see a change in political sentiment which allowed them to revive their novitiate in 1828. WWII bombing destroyed their house, but the community rebuilt and still exists under the same name today. The Dominican sisters of the Katharinenkloster Augsburg (or Kloster St. Katharina) were established in 1243 in a suburb (Am Gries) of Augsburg but moved into the city proper in 1251. They, too, were secularized in 1802 and forced to vacate their buildings in 1807. This foundation is defunct. The Dominican sisters of Kloster St. Margaret moved to the city in 1261 from their original home at monastery of Leuthau at Klimmach (founded 1241). Their house burned in 1333; a new church and cloister were finally completed in 1521. In 1534 the Augsburger authorities closed the church to public worship and the community was disbanded in 1538. This foundation is defunct.
So there you are: Everything You Wanted To Know About Augsburger Dominican History, But Were Afraid To Ask.

comment.text: First German edition of Platina's Vitae Pontificum, comissioned by a German Renaissance prince, Count Palatine Ottheinrich, at the suggestion of his advisor, the Reformer Kaspar Hedio. Hedio translated Palatina's Vitae Pontificum into German and carefully indexed all those passages that could be used to support Protestant claims to Reform. He also added a register who directs the reader to those passages in the Lives which have a bearing on Reformed ideas. This is the culmination of what can be regarded as censorship in reverse and a valuable example of how Platina was read and used by a moderate Reformer in the mid-sixteenth century. Cf. Stefan Bauer. Censorship and Fortuna of Platina's Lives of the Popes in the Sixteenth Century.

comment.text: The writer of the verses is probably Johannes Hadus, an early 16th-century humanist and Latin poet. His presence in the historical record is erratic. His PND database entry gives his birth as ca. 1488; he is last heard from in Italy in 1524. He was extremely peripatetic; after stints in Wittenberg, Frankfurt an der Oder, Greifswald, Rostock, and Kraków, he arrived in Vienna in 1516. He had some notable success there, including being named poet laureate by the Holy Roman Emperor Maximilian I. He subsequently left for Rome; his last known publication appeared in Blosius Palladius's 1524 anthology of poems in honor of Janus Coricius, Coryciana (Impressum Rom[a]e : Apud Ludouicum Vicentinum et Lautitium Perusinum, mense Iulio MDXXIIII).

Crest: on a wreath, a lion's gamb erected and erased, or, holding a branch, vert, fructed, gules.), with earl's coronet and motto "Tuum est," engraved by "Cole". Several engravers named Cole were active in producing bookplates in the 18th century; cf. H.W. Fincham, Artists and Engravers of British and American Bookplates (London: Kegan Paul, Trench, Trübner & Co., 1897), p. 18ff. This is perhaps the work of M. Cole for Earl Cowper ca. 1730 -- that would be William Clavering-Cowper, 2nd Earl Cowper (1709-1764), who succeeded to the title in 1723. According to E. Hasted in The History and Topographical Survey of the County of Kent, 2nd ed., v. 9 (Canterbury: Bristow, 1800), p. 64, William "some time before [his death] prefixed the surname and arms of Clavering to his own, according to the will of his mother's brother" [i.e. John Clavering, 1698-1762]." This bookplate would predate that event. (The book to which it is affixed, Nummi Britannici Historia, or, An Historical Account of English Money was printed in London by W. Meadows in 1726.)

comment.text:
The identification of "Episcopatus Neostadiensis" with the Diocese of Wiener-Neustadt is perhaps strengthened by the (as yet unphotographed) gift inscription on the back pastedown of this work:
Per [Reverend]um[?] do. Vrbanu[m] Ep[iscopu]m Labacen[sem] ex Wormaria allatus : et dono dat[us] Prag[a]e Ligatus. 3. Septembr[is]. 1545.
"Urbanus Episcopus Labacensis" would be Urban Textor (i.e. Weber or Tkalec), d. 1558, who was the Roman Catholic bishop of Laibach (now Ljubljana, Slovenia) from 1543-1558 and almoner, confessor, and briefly court preacher (ca. 1555 for that last) to the Holy Roman Emperor Ferdinand I in Vienna. Which at least gets the book into the general vicinity of Wiener-Neustadt. (According to contemporary accounts, Textor died of a fall on an icy staircase in Kloster Heilig Kreuz in Donauwörth, Germany. His Reformation opponents were generally of the opinion that God gave him a push so the Devil could have him. Cf. two poems on the subject, including one by Matthias Flacius Illyricus, quoted in T. Wiedemann, Geschichte der Reformation und Gegenreformation im Lande unter der Enns (Prag: Tempsky, 1879), v. 1, p. 101.)

comment.author: 58584977@N05
comment.text:
Just to disambiguate:  this bookplate is not that of any Duke of Arenberg, though the book itself is likely to have been part of their library after 1903.

The current Schloss Nordkirchen (which replaced an earlier moated castle) was constructed in several stages between 1703 and 1734 under the ownership of Friedrich Christian von Plettenberg zu Lenhausen (1644-1706), Bishop of Münster, and his nephew Ferdinand von Plettenberg (1690-1737), founder of the Plettenberg-Wittem branch of the family.  Its male line ended with Maximilian von Plettenberg-Wittem zu Mietingen (1771-1813); his daughter, Mária von Plettenberg-Wittem (1809-1861), brought Nordkirchen as part of her dowry upon marrying Miklós Ferenc Esterházy de Galántha [or Nikolaus Franz Esterházy von Galantha -- he's not established] (1804-1885) in 1823.  The bookplate is theirs, as mfraas notes, with an aggroupment of their blazons:  his on the left, hers on the right.

In 1903 Nordkirchen was alienated from the Esterházy family to Herzog Engelbert-Maria von Arenberg (1872-1949), the 9th duke of Arenberg, who inherited its "superbe bibliothèque" as well as that of his father, "un grand collectioneur" (Lemaire, p. 83, 85).  His son Engelbert-Karl (1899-1974), the 10th duke, began selling off the ducal library in 1951 (cf. Lemaire p. 91); this book was purchased by the Penn Libraries in 1952.  (We have at least four other volumes with Nordkirchen provenance in our collections, including one also autographed by Ferdinand von Plettenberg.)

Finishing off the story of Nordkirchen:  it was sold in 1959 to the state of Nordrhein-Westfalen, in whose possession it remains a tourist attraction and the site of the Fachhochschule für Finanzen Nordrhein-Westfalen (since 1958).

The printer’s device of Mathias Apiarius (ca. 1500-1554) features a bear discovering a bee's nest in the hollow of a tree.  At the base of the tree there is a Bible and bees are flying around. The device also features one inscription in Greek  and three inscriptions in Latin (Below:  "Omnia probate, quod bonum fuerit tenete. 1. Thess. 5.;
 On the right side: "Quam dulcia faucibus meis eloquia tua, super mel orimeo. Psal. 118. 
On the left side:  "Vrsus insidians & esuriens, princeps impius super populum pauperem. Thre. 3. Prouerb. 28. )
The inscriptions help to explain the meaning of the woodcut: the bear is about to remove a huge mallet hung upon a branch before the hole which contains honey; the mallet will naturally always fall back on him.
